<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The tragic loss of the space shuttle Colombia has left America, and much of the world, reeling.  As we search for answers in the wake of this terrible event, we must also consider the future of the space program.  Where do we go from here?<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The loss of Colombia equates to a 25% loss in the shuttle fleet.  A significantly long grounding of the shuttle fleet is not impossible, and so our capacity maybe be reduced to very little very soon.  This void must be filled, and why not fill it with a newer, cheaper, and more efficient launch system?<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The experimental, “X” flights conducted by NASA have been very successful, yet they have been cancelled shortly after their trial runs.  A new Orbital Space Plane initiative is underway, but doubts have been expressed as to whether it will be seen to successful development.  It is absolutely essential that we stop wasting money on these programs, and start demanding results.  A cheaper space plane would equate to a larger fleet, which would be less vulnerable to catastrophic loss.  A shorter gap between missions would be possible, due to the larger fleet.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp This new capability is imperative if we intend to have a suitable service to the International Space Station.  We cannot spend $500 million to $1 billion per launch to the ISS, and we cannot simply let the ISS go to waste.  This scenario further demands new capabilities.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Project Prometheus is another program that should be pushed harder than before.  Now, more than ever, our space capabilities are in jeopardy.  We stand up to these tragic events with a fresh approach to space, one that allows us to achieve more than ever before.  More efficient boosters will help us accomplish this.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The most terrible result of the loss of the Colombia would be to let the deaths of the crew to be in vain.  We must press forward with our space program, in honor of their great sacrifice.  Anything less would be an insult to those who paid the ultimate price for what they believed in.<br>
