This is simply untrue. There are so many designs which are more economical, safer and reliable than the Shuttle. For example it is perfectly possible with today's technology to build a VTOL SSTO vehicle. No solid rocket boosters (improves safety by a factor of at least 10), no throw-away external tank (makes it more economical), no wings (no dead stick landing, structurally more stable). Another option would be an HTOL SSTO spaceplane although that would require scramjet technology to be perfected first. I'm all for nuclear power in space but we don't need it to get CATS. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=oberth>oberth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/03 2:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=740.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Re The wake of the Columbia</span><hr size=1> &quot;I think that NASA should phase out the shuttle. Do NOT order a replacement orbiter for Columbia as was done with Challenger. Instead, use the estimated $3 Billion to develop a small space plane that only carries people, no cargo.&quot;<br>
